It is straightforward to check the the full algebra is closed (the commutation relations are gathered
in Appendix) and we conclude that the Hamiltonian () governs the dynamics of an
 invariant extension of the two-particle Calogero model. Notice that in the one-particle limit
(i.e. setting , , )
the system () reproduces the  superconformal mechanics of Ref. (with the parameters , ; see  for more details).
A few comments are in order.

i) Let us compare our result with the previous attempts , to construct an
 superconformal extension of the Calogero model. According to the analysis of
Ref.  for generic values of the coupling constant  and for  there is no way to build
an  invariant extension, while for  this can be done only for a particular value of the
coupling constant (see Ref.  for more details). As we have seen above, taking a more general ansatz
for the supersymmetry generators one can weaken the restriction on the coupling constant and construct a two-particle
model for generic values of the coupling constant(A passage to the center of mass and relative coordinates in the
Hamiltonian of the two-particle Calogero model brings it to the sum of a free particle and the conformal
mechanics , both admitting an  superconformal extension. Thus, the existence of an 
invariant extension of the two-particle Calogero model for an arbitrary value of the coupling constant
might be anticipated on this general ground. We thank Sergey Krivonos for pointing this out to us.) .
In Ref.  an -invariant model in two dimensions has been constructed without any restrictions
on the coupling constant or the number of particles. Since a naive dimensional reduction to one dimension does not
preserve all four supersymmetries it seems interesting to search for a more sophisticated reduction.

ii) Although we did not try to systematically extend our analysis to the  case, a preliminary consideration
shows that this may require a modification of the  representation ().
One such possibility is to mix fermions in the -generators so that the fermions belonging to
different particles share the same  spinor representation. For example, for the
three-particle case the generators
